Layers
======

This directory contains a set of composable Flax Modules. Each module (or layer)
follows one of the following two patterns:

1. Direct pattern (for small modules)
-------------------------------------

The module takes a set of constructor arguments and implements a call method
with a training: bool variable without a default value.

Usage example:

  m = MyModule(a=1, b=2)
  y = m(x, training=True)

2. Configuration-based pattern
------------------------------

For each module <Name>, a dataclass <Name>Config implements a make method
returning the <Name> module.

Usage example:

  config = MyModuleConfig(a=1, b=2)
  m = config.make()
  y = m(x, training=True)

Note that nothing prevent the user to do:

  m = MyModuleConfig(a=1, b=2).make()
  y = m(x, training=True)

This make approach create a nice solution to the solution of versionning.
While the following is possibly, it is not ideal (would break the versioning).

  MyModuleConfig can create MyModuleV1 or MyModuleV2

Note: Configuring modules with dataclasses greatly simplifies model
serialization. When using the direct pattern for layers with many configuration
options, the caller must manage serialization manually, a task made much easier
by dataclasses.

Note: The module class should not repeat all the fields from the config, as it
creates code that is harder to maintain.

Schemas (e.g., graph, feature), graph stats, and other large configuration data
should be provided as constructor arguments of the make function instead of
being stored in the config.

  config = MyModuleConfig(a=1, b=2)
  m = config.make(schema=my_graph_schema)
  y = m(x, training=True)
